ationDateTime\":\"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z\",\"Entity\":\"videopid\",\"Guid\":\"\",\"Id\":\"p04ftx4f\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z\",\"Project\":\"\",\"Slug\":\"\"},\"Thumbnail\":[{\"Content\":{\"Copyright\":\"\",\"FileSizeBytes\":92038,\"MimeType\":\"image/jpeg\",\"SourceHeight\":1080,\"SourceUrl\":\"https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/live-galileo-interface-mt-resources-imagebucket-1a92e5tj3b5d6/p0/4f/ty/p04ftyf7.jpg\",\"SourceWidth\":1920,\"SynopsisLong\":\"\",\"SynopsisMedium\":\"\",\"SynopsisShort\":\"The history of thinking machines\",\"TemplateUrl\":\"http://ichef.bbci.co.uk/wwfeatures/$recipe/images/live/p0/4f/ty/p04ftyf7.jpg\",\"Title\":\"WCIS AI video\",\"CreationDateTime\":\"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z\",\"Entity\":\"\",\"Guid\":\"\",\"Id\":\"p04ftyf7\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z\",\"Project\":\"\",\"Slug\":\"\"},\"Metadata\":{\"CreationDateTime\":\"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z\",\"Entity\":\"\",\"Guid\":\"\",\"Id\":\"p04ftyf7\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z\",\"Project\":\"\",\"Slug\":\"\"},\"Urn\":\"urn:pubstack:jative:image:p04ftyf7\",\"_id\":\"5b424b9bfa2f32dd66d79a25\"}],\"Title\":\"WCIS AI video\",\"Urn\":\"urn:pubstack:jative:videopid:p04ftx4f\",\"Vpid\":\"p04ftx54\",\"WarningLong\":\"\",\"WarningShort\":\"\",\"_id\":\"5b3e9442fa2f32dd66d5a365\"}],\"AssetVideoMps\":null,\"Author\":null,\"BodyHtml\":\"<p><a href=\\\"http://www.bbc.com/future/columns/world-changing-ideas\\\"><img src=\\\"http://ichef.bbci.co.uk/images/ic/raw/p049vjvx.png\\\" border=\\\"0\\\" alt=\\\"World-changing ideas summit\\\" width=\\\"100%\\\" /></a></p><p>It was renowned British computer scientist Alan Turing &ndash; the man who helped crack the Nazi Enigma code &ndash; who first came up with a test to see if a machine could show the kind of intelligent behavior seen in humans.</p><p>In the decades since the Turing test was proposed, computers have become so intelligent that we often don&rsquo;t realise when we&rsquo;re talking to them. That helpful customer services rep who assisted you through your problems over a messaging service? Probably a chatbot, programmed to react to key words contained in your requests.</p><p>We have gone from computers that can bamboozle a chess grandmaster to intelligent systems that will drive our cars. Watch the video above to see what else our learning servants may one day take off our hands.</p><p><em>Join 700,000+ Future fans by liking us on</em> <a href=\\\"https://www.facebook.com/BBCFuture\\\"><strong><em>Facebook</em></strong></a><em>, or follow us on</em> <a href=\\\"https://twitter.com/bbc_future\\\"><strong><em>Twitter</em></strong></a><em>,</em> <a href=\\\"https://plus.google.com/107828172298602173375/posts\\\"><strong><em>Google+</em></strong></a><em>,</em> <a href=\\\"https://www.linkedin.com/company/bbc-com\\\"><strong><em>LinkedIn</em></strong></a> <em>and </em><a href=\\\"https://instagram.com/bbcfuture_official/\\\"><strong><em>Instagram</em></strong></a></p><p><em>If you liked this story,&nbsp;</em><a href=\\\"http://pages.emails.bbc.com/subscribe/\\\"><em>sign up for the weekly bbc.com features newsletter</em></a><em>, called &ldquo;If You Only Read 6 Things This Week</em><em>&rdquo;. A handpicked selection of stories from BBC Future, Earth, Culture, Capital, Travel and Autos, delivered to your inbox every Friday.</em></p>\",\"BusinessUnit\":\"worldwide\",\"CalloutBody\":\"\",\"CalloutPosition\":\"\",\"CalloutSubtitle\":\"\",\"CalloutTitle\":\"\",\"Campaign\":null,\"Collection\":[{\"Content\":{\"AssetImage\":[{\"Content\":{\"Copyright\":\"\",\"FileSizeBytes\":57657,\"MimeType\":\"image/jpeg\",\"SourceHeight\":576,\"SourceUrl\":\"http://deltaorigin.bbc.co.uk/images/live/p0/17/4f/p0174fgv.jpg\",\"SourceWidth\":1024,\"SynopsisLong\":\"World-Changing Ideas\",\"SynopsisMedium\":\"World-Changing Ideas\",\"SynopsisShort\":\"World-Changing Ideas\",\"TemplateUrl\":\"http://ichef.bbci.co.uk/wwfeatures/$recipe/images/live/p0/17/4f/p0174fgv.jpg\",\"Title\":\"WorldChangingIdeas-ColumnGraphic.jpg\",\"CreationDateTime\":\"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z\",\"Entity\":\"\",\"Guid\":\"\",\"Id\":\"p0174fgv\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z\",\"Project\":\"\",\"Slug\":\"\"},\"Metadata\":{\"CreationDateTime\":\"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z\",\"Entity\":\"\",\"Guid\":\"\",\"Id\":\"p0174fgv\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z\",\"Project\":\"\",\"Slug\":\"\"},\"Urn\":\"urn:pubstack:jative:image:p0174fgv\",\"_id\":\"5b401e70fa2f32dd66d672ae\"}],\"Campaign\":null,\"CollectionOverrides\":null,\"CollectionType\":\"column\",\"Description\":\"Fascinating stories, need-to-know briefings and compelling video inspired by BBC Future's World-Changing Ideas event series, next on in Sydney on 15 November 2016.\",\"Name\":\"World-Changing Ideas\",\"Partner\":null,\"PrimaryVertical\":\"wwfuture\",\"Title\":\"World-Changing Ideas\",\"CreationDateTime\":\"2015-05-20T11:04:06.894444Z\",\"Entity\":\"collection\",\"Guid\":\"58a318ae-63bd-40fd-953b-a783283ba763\",\"Id\":\"wwfuture/column/world-changing-ideas\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"2016-10-12T12:27:58.674723Z\",\"Project\":\"wwfuture\",\"Slug\":\"column/world-changing-ideas\"},\"Metadata\":{\"CreationDateTime\":\"2015-05-20T11:04:06.894444Z\",\"Entity\":\"collection\",\"Guid\":\"58a318ae-63bd-40fd-953b-a783283ba763\",\"Id\":\"wwfuture/column/world-changing-ideas\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"2016-10-12T12:27:58.674723Z\",\"Project\":\"wwfuture\",\"Slug\":\"column/world-changing-ideas\"},\"Urn\":\"urn:pubstack:jative:collection:wwfuture/column/world-changing-ideas\",\"_id\":\"5b3b1a4ffa2f32dd66d1be96\"}],\"DisableAdverts\":false,\"DisplayDate\":\"2016-11-14T10:22:54.509Z\",\"Geolocation\":null,\"HeadlineLong\":\"How we built machines that can think for themselves\",\"HeadlineShort\":\"How we built machines that can think\",\"HideRelated\":false,\"Horizontal\":null,\"Intro\":\"The computers we have built are now capable of thinking for themselves, and doing complex jobs without our supervision. Where does it go from here? \",\"IsSyndicated\":false,\"Location\":null,\"Option\":null,\"Partner\":null,\"PrimaryVertical\":\"wwfuture\",\"Programme\":null,\"RelatedStory\":[{\"Content\":{\"AssetCustom\":\"\",\"AssetIbroadcast\":null,\"AssetImage\":[{\"Content\":{\"Copyright\":\"iStock\",\"FileSizeBytes\":247317,\"MimeType\":\"image/jpeg\",\"SourceHeight\":1080,\"SourceUrl\":\"https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/live-galileo-interface-mt-resources-imagebucket-1a92e5tj3b5d6/p0/4f/q8/p04fq8qx.jpg\",\"SourceWidth\":1920,\"SynopsisLong\":\"\",\"SynopsisMedium\":\"\",\"SynopsisShort\":\"(Credit: iStock)\",\"TemplateUrl\":\"http://ichef.bbci.co.uk/wwfeatures/$recipe/images/live/p0/4f/q8/p04fq8qx.jpg\",\"Title\":\"soyuz_istock_1920.jpg\",\"CreationDateTime\":\"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z\",\"Entity\":\"\",\"Guid\":\"\",\"Id\":\"p04fq8qx\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z\",\"Project\":\"\",\"Slug\":\"\"},\"Metadata\":{\"CreationDateTime\":\"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z\",\"Entity\":\"\",\"Guid\":\"\",\"Id\":\"p04fq8qx\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z\",\"Project\":\"\",\"Slug\":\"\"},\"Urn\":\"urn:pubstack:jative:image:p04fq8qx\",\"_id\":\"5b45d9fffa2f32dd66d979cb\"}],\"AssetImagePromo\":null,\"AssetInfographic\":\"\",\"AssetInline\":null,\"AssetSelect\":\"ib2video\",\"AssetVideoIb2\":[{\"Duration\":129,\"Metadata\":{\"CreationDateTime\":\"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z\",\"Entity\":\"videopid\",\"Guid\":\"\",\"Id\":\"p04fq3hf\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z\",\"Project\":\"\",\"Slug\":\"\"},\"Thumbnail\":[],\"Title\":\"How we made it into space\",\"Urn\":\"urn:pubstack:jative:videopid:p04fq3hf\",\"Vpid\":\"p04fq3hl\",\"WarningLong\":\"\",\"WarningShort\":\"\",\"_id\":\"5b41dc0cfa2f32dd66d75d6b\"}],\"AssetVideoMps\":null,\"Author\":null,\"BodyHtml\":\"<p><a href=\\\"http://www.bbc.com/future/columns/world-changing-ideas\\\"><img src=\\\"http://ichef.bbci.co.uk/images/ic/raw/p049vjvx.png\\\" border=\\\"0\\\" alt=\\\"World-changing ideas summit\\\" width=\\\"100%\\\" /></a></p><p>In the 17th Century, the Italian astronomer and scientist Galileo peered into his telescope and drew the first simple map of the Moon, sketching the craters and mountains viewed through polished glass.</p><p>It took more than three hundred years for humanity to stop merely looking and begin actually exploring the Solar System we live in.</p><p>It was the Soviets who got there first, launching the satellite Sputnik in 1957. Dogs and chimpanzees, packed into primitive spacecraft, followed next. And then it was people, beginning with the grinning cosmonaut Yuri Gagarin, through to Moon-walker Neil Armstrong and the crews who flew Space Shuttles, manned space stations, and took pictures of Earth that showed us a new view of the planet we call home.</p><p>Our journey through space is only one of the topics covered in our World Changing Ideas Summit held in Sydney on 15 November. Watch the video above to see how far we&rsquo;ve come &ndash; and what we plan to explore next.</p><p><em>Join 700,000+ Future fans by liking us on</em> <a href=\\\"https://www.facebook.com/BBCFuture\\\"><strong><em>Facebook</em></strong></a><em>, or follow us on</em> <a href=\\\"https://twitter.com/bbc_future\\\"><strong><em>Twitter</em></strong></a><em>,</em> <a href=\\\"https://plus.google.com/107828172298602173375/posts\\\"><strong><em>Google+</em></strong></a><em>,</em> <a href=\\\"https://www.linkedin.com/company/bbc-com\\\"><strong><em>LinkedIn</em></strong></a> <em>and </em><a href=\\\"https://instagram.com/bbcfuture_official/\\\"><strong><em>Instagram</em></strong></a></p><p><em>If you liked this story,&nbsp;</em><a href=\\\"http://pages.emails.bbc.com/subscribe/\\\"><em>sign up for the weekly bbc.com features newsletter</em></a><em>, called &ldquo;If You Only Read 6 Things This Week</em><em>&rdquo;. A handpicked selection of stories from BBC Future, Earth, Culture, Capital, Travel and Autos, delivered to your inbox every Friday.</em></p>\",\"BusinessUnit\":\"worldwide\",\"CalloutBody\":\"\",\"CalloutPosition\":\"\",\"CalloutSubtitle\":\"\",\"CalloutTitle\":\"\",\"Campaign\":null,\"Collection\":[{\"Content\":{\"AssetImage\":[],\"Campaign\":null,\"CollectionOverrides\":null,\"CollectionType\":\"column\",\"Description\":\"Fascinating stories, need-to-know briefings and compelling video inspired by BBC Future's World-Changing Ideas event series, next on in Sydney on 15 November 2016.\",\"Name\":\"World-Changing Ideas\",\"Partner\":null,\"PrimaryVertical\":\"wwfuture\",\"Title\":\"World-Changing Ideas\",\"CreationDateTime\":\"2015-05-20T11:04:06.894444Z\",\"Entity\":\"collection\",\"Guid\":\"58a318ae-63bd-40fd-953b-a783283ba763\",\"Id\":\"wwfuture/column/world-changing-ideas\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"2016-10-12T12:27:58.674723Z\",\"Project\":\"wwfuture\",\"Slug\":\"column/world-changing-ideas\"},\"Metadata\":{\"CreationDateTime\":\"2015-05-20T11:04:06.894444Z\",\"Entity\":\"collection\",\"Guid\":\"58a318ae-63bd-40fd-953b-a783283ba763\",\"Id\":\"wwfuture/column/world-changing-ideas\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"2016-10-12T12:27:58.674723Z\",\"Project\":\"wwfuture\",\"Slug\":\"column/world-changing-ideas\"},\"Urn\":\"urn:pubstack:jative:collection:wwfuture/column/world-changing-ideas\",\"_id\":\"5b3b1a4ffa2f32dd66d1be96\"}],\"DisableAdverts\":false,\"DisplayDate\":\"2016-11-12T13:46:19Z\",\"Geolocation\":null,\"HeadlineLong\":\"How humanity took a bold leap into the cosmos \",\"HeadlineShort\":\"From Sputnik to colonising Mars \",\"HideRelated\":false,\"Horizontal\":null,\"Intro\":\"In little more than 50 years, we have gone from staring up at the heavens to the first tentative steps to colonising another planet.\\n\",\"IsSyndicated\":false,\"Location\":null,\"Option\":null,\"Partner\":null,\"PrimaryVertical\":\"wwfuture\",\"Programme\":null,\"RelatedStory\":[{\"Content\":{\"AssetCustom\":\"\",\"AssetIbroadcast\":null,\"AssetImage\":[],\"AssetImagePromo\":null,\"AssetInfographic\":\"\",\"AssetInline\":null,\"AssetSelect\":\"ib2video\",\"AssetVideoIb2\":[],\"AssetVideoMps\":null,\"Author\":null,\"BodyHtml\":\"<p>Many thousands of years ago, the first primitive humans took a step that would change the species forever &ndash; they made the first primitive ovens.</p><p>Cooking food &ndash; and back in those days it was more likely to be a woolly mammoth than a juicy burger &ndash; changed our diet, and ultimately ourselves. Cooking was the first human act to refine food. And it&rsquo;s that refining &ndash; whether by farming or processing the raw resources into something more edible &ndash; that has allowed humanity to spread across the globe.</p><p>It has fuelled the growth of human settlements, bred international trade and powered the huge cities that define human habitation in the 21st Century.</p><p>But it has created problems &ndash; with easier access to food, humanity&rsquo;s population has exploded. And producing and moving the food we eat needs vast amounts of energy, contributing greatly to climate change.</p><p>How do we continue to feed ourselves without harming the planet? This will be one of the questions asked at BBC Future&rsquo;s World Changing Ideas Summit in Sydney on 15 November. Watch the video above to get a taste of what will be discussed.</p><p><em>Join 700,000+ Future fans by liking us on</em> <a href=\\\"https://www.facebook.com/BBCFuture\\\"><strong><em>Facebook</em></strong></a><em>, or follow us on</em> <a href=\\\"https://twitter.com/bbc_future\\\"><strong><em>Twitter</em></strong></a><em>,</em> <a href=\\\"https://plus.google.com/107828172298602173375/posts\\\"><strong><em>Google+</em></strong></a><em>,</em> <a href=\\\"https://www.linkedin.com/company/bbc-com\\\"><strong><em>LinkedIn</em></strong></a> <em>and </em><a href=\\\"https://instagram.com/bbcfuture_official/\\\"><strong><em>Instagram</em></strong></a></p><p><em>If you liked this story,&nbsp;</em><a href=\\\"http://pages.emails.bbc.com/subscribe/\\\"><em>sign up for the weekly bbc.com features newsletter</em></a><em>, called &ldquo;If You Only Read 6 Things This Week</em><em>&rdquo;. A handpicked selection of stories from BBC Future, Earth, Culture, Capital, Travel and Autos, delivered to your inbox every Friday.</em></p>\",\"BusinessUnit\":\"worldwide\",\"CalloutBody\":\"\",\"CalloutPosition\":\"\",\"CalloutSubtitle\":\"\",\"CalloutTitle\":\"\",\"Campaign\":null,\"Collection\":[],\"DisableAdverts\":false,\"DisplayDate\":\"2016-11-09T10:00:32.12Z\",\"Geolocation\":null,\"HeadlineLong\":\"How what we eat has changed \u2013 and will change again\",\"HeadlineShort\":\"How what we eat has changed \",\"HideRelated\":false,\"Horizontal\":null,\"Intro\":\"We\u2019ve gone from roasting to processing over thousands of years. What does the future hold for our food? Watch the video above to see what we\u2019ll be eating in decades to come.\\n\",\"IsSyndicated\":false,\"Location\":null,\"Option\":null,\"Partner\":null,\"PrimaryVertical\":\"wwfuture\",\"Programme\":null,\"RelatedStory\":[],\"RelatedTag\":null,\"StoryType\":\"video\",\"SummaryLong\":\"We\u2019ve gone from roasting to processing over thousands of years. What does the future hold for our food?\",\"SummaryShort\":\"A short history of human appetite\",\"Tag\":[]},\"Metadata\":{\"CreationDateTime\":\"2016-11-09T10:13:50.119354Z\",\"Entity\":\"story\",\"Guid\":\"3217daf7-3e87-4cb1-b5e9-eb786e783f5c\",\"Id\":\"wwfuture/story/20161109-how-what-we-eat-has-changed-and-will-change-again\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"2016-11-09T10:28:47.16043Z\",\"Project\":\"wwfuture\",\"Slug\":\"20161109-how-what-we-eat-has-changed-and-will-change-again\"},\"Urn\":\"urn:pubstack:jative:story:wwfuture/story/20161109-how-what-we-eat-has-changed-and-will-change-again\",\"_id\":\"5b42781cfa2f32dd66d7b112\"},{\"Content\":{\"AssetCustom\":\"\",\"AssetIbroadcast\":null,\"AssetImage\":[],\"AssetImagePromo\":null,\"AssetInfographic\":\"\",\"AssetInline\":[],\"AssetSelect\":\"\",\"AssetVideoIb2\":null,\"AssetVideoMps\":null,\"Author\":[],\"BodyHtml\":\"<p><a href=\\\"http://www.bbc.com/future/columns/world-changing-ideas\\\"><img src=\\\"http://ichef.bbci.co.uk/images/ic/raw/p049vjvx.png\\\" border=\\\"0\\\" alt=\\\"World-changing ideas summit\\\" width=\\\"100%\\\" /></a></p><p>The guests lining up outside a Brisbane gallery were not your typical culture vultures; in fact, until recently they&rsquo;d never seen a painting in their life. But with just a little training, they developed their own artistic taste, showing a clear preference for Picasso&rsquo;s crystalline constructions or Monet&rsquo;s dreamy soft focus as they wandered lazily through the different rooms.</p><p>It&rsquo;s little wonder that their talents created such a buzz, considering that they were working with a brain smaller than a pin head: these bona fide art critics were your <a href=\\\"http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s00359-012-0767-5%20/fulltext.html\\\">common or garden honey bees</a>, trained to find a syrupy surprise behind one or other of the artists' work.</p><p>In fact, the ability to recognise artistic style was just the latest in a long list of achievements. Honey bees can <a href=\\\"http://www.livescience.com/2909-bees-count.html\\\">count up to four</a>, read complex signs, learn from observation and talk to each other in a secret code (the famous &lsquo;waggle dance&rsquo;). When foraging, they can weigh up the distance to different flowers, planning complex routes to collect the most nectar with the least effort. And within the hive, their individual responsibilities can include cleaning, undertaking (as they tend to the dead) and even air-conditioning, as they collect water to drop on the honey comb during hot weather.</p><p>{\\\"image\\\":{\\\"pid\\\":\\\"p04fm458\\\"}}</p><p>The human brain has nearly 100,000 times as many neurons as the bee brain, yet the rudiments of many of our most valued behaviours can be seen in the teeming activity of the hive. So what&rsquo;s the point of all that grey matter we hold in our skulls? And how does it set us apart from other animals? These are some of the questions that will be discussed at the <a href=\\\"https://www.worldchangingideas.com.au/world-changing-ideas-summit-2016\\\">BBC Future&rsquo;s World-Changing Ideas Summit in Sydney on 15 November</a>.</p><p><strong>ARE BIG BRAINS A WASTE OF SPACE?</strong></p><p>About one-fifth of all you eat is used to power the electrical chit-chat between your 100 billion little grey cells. If a big brain didn&rsquo;t give us any advantage, that would be an enormous waste.</p><p>And there are some clear benefits. If nothing else, it makes us more efficient at what we do. If honey bees are searching a scene, for instance, they will consider each object one by one, whereas larger animals have the extra brainpower to process it all at once. We can multi-task, in other words.</p><p>A bigger brain also boosts the amount we can remember: a honey bee can grasp just a handful of associations between signs signalling the presence of food, before it starts getting confused, whereas even a pigeon can learn to recognise more than 1,800 pictures, and that&rsquo;s nothing compared to human knowledge. For a comparison, consider that a memory champions can remember the sequence of Pi to literally thousands of decimal places.</p><p><strong>OK, SO WE CAN REMEMBER A LOT. WHAT ELSE?</strong></p><p>Darwin described these kinds of distinctions as &ldquo;differences of degree, not kind&rdquo; &ndash; a conclusion that some might find frustrating. If you look at human civilisation and all we have achieved, surely we must have some particularly special ability that is completely lacking in all other animals?</p><p>Culture, technology, altruism and many other traits have all been touted as signs of human greatness &ndash; but the more you look, the narrower that list becomes.</p><p>{\\\"image\\\":{\\\"pid\\\":\\\"p04fm4kp\\\"}}</p><p>Macaques, for instance, have long been known to pick up stones to crack nuts while <a href=\\\"http://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-35159872\\\">New Caledonian crows can craft hooks from a broken stick to help them pick up food</a> - both rudimentary forms of tool use. Even invertebrates are getting in on the act. Veined octopuses, for instance, appear to collect coconut shells, <a href=\\\"https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2009/12/091214121953.htm\\\">dragging them along the sea floor</a> for later use as a shelter.&nbsp;</p><p>A chimp in Zambia, meanwhile, has been caught <a href=\\\"http://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/animal-fashion-some-chimps-are-putting-grass-ears-and-nobody-knows-why-180951888/?no-ist\\\">wearing a fetching tuft of grass in her ear</a> &ndash; apparently for no other reason than that she thought it looked nice. Soon, many of the other chimps in her group copied her fashion statement, a form of adornment that some researchers have interpreted as a form of cultural expression.&nbsp;</p><p>Many creatures also seem to have an innate sense of fairness, and may even feel empathy for others &ndash; <a href=\\\"http://www.bbc.com/earth/story/20150706-humans-are-not-unique-or-special\\\">as our colleagues at BBC Earth recently explored</a> &ndash; again suggesting a kind of rich emotional life that was once thought to be our specie's domain. Consider the case of a humpback whale, which was recently seen saving a seal&rsquo;s life, <a href=\\\"https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg23230950-700-i-saw-humpback-whales-save-a-seal-from-death-by-killer-whale/\\\">protecting it from a killer whale attack</a> &ndash; evidence that we are not the only animal to behave altruistically.</p><p><strong>HOW ABOUT CONSCIOUS THOUGHT?</strong></p><p>Perhaps the answer instead lies in a &ldquo;sense of self&rdquo;, a creature&rsquo;s ability to recognise itself as an individual. This navel gazing would be a rudimentary form of consciousness. Of all the different qualities that might make us unique, self-awareness is the toughest to measure with any certainty &ndash; but one common test involved daubing a spot of paint on the animal, and putting it in front of a mirror. If the animal notices the mark and tries to rub it off, we can assume that the animal recognises its reflection, suggesting it has formed some kind of concept about itself.</p><p>Humans don&rsquo;t develop this capacity until they are around 18-months-old, but a handful of other animals appear to demonstrated this kind of awareness, including <a href=\\\"http://www.animalcognition.org/2015/04/15/list-of-animals-that-have-passed-the-mirror-test/\\\">bonobos, chimps, orang-utans, gorillas, magpies, dolphins and orca whales</a>.</p><p>{\\\"image\\\":{\\\"pid\\\":\\\"p04fm4lr\\\"}}</p><p><strong>SO WE&rsquo;RE NOTHING SPECIAL AFTER ALL?</strong></p><p>Not so fast. A couple of mental capacities may be purely our own, and they are perhaps best understood by considering a family&rsquo;s conversation around the dinner table.</p><p>The first astonishing fact is that we can speak at all, of course. No matter what you&rsquo;ve been thinking and feeling throughout the day, you will be able to find words to express the experience and describe it to those around you.&nbsp;</p><p>No other creature can communicate with such freedom. The honey bee&rsquo;s waggle dance, for instance, can relay the location of a flower bed, and it can even warn the other bees about the presence of a dangerous insect, but it can&rsquo;t express everything the bee has experienced: it is limited to a few facts about the immediate circumstances. <a href=\\\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0262407910629612\\\">Human language, in contrast, is open-ended</a>. With infinite combinations of words to choose from, we can articulate our deepest feelings or lay down the rules of physics &ndash; and if we can&rsquo;t quite find the right term, we can just invent a new one.</p><p>What&rsquo;s even more remarkable though, is the fact that most of our conversation is not rooted in the present, but revolves around the past and the future, which brings us to one of the other traits that may define us. We&rsquo;ve already explored how we may be able to recall more facts than most animals. This is &lsquo;semantic&rsquo; memory. But as Thomas Suddendorf at the University of Queensland will point out at the World-Changing Ideas Summit, we also have &lsquo;episodic&rsquo; recall &ndash; the ability to mentally relive past events, picturing them in multi-sensory detail. It&rsquo;s the difference between knowing that Paris is the capital of France, and being able to bring back the sights and sounds of your first trip to the Louvre.</p><p>{\\\"image\\\":{\\\"pid\\\":\\\"p04fm4xh\\\"}}</p><p>Crucially, the ability to think back to the past also allows us to imagine the future, too, as we use previous experiences to predict future scenarios. You might imagine your next holiday by recalling all your past trips, for instance, allowing you to picture what kind of hotel you like, plan the sights you want to visit and build a menu of food you want to eat.</p><p>No other animal appears to have such elaborate personal memories, combined with the ability to plan whole chains of actions in advance. Even bees, with their complicated housekeeping in the hive, are probably only responding to their present circumstances; their thoughts don&rsquo;t go beyond the next flower they would like to visit or the danger of an intruder. They are not going to reminisce about what it felt like to be a larva.&nbsp;</p><p>Together with language, mental &lsquo;time travel&rsquo; allows us to share our experiences and our hopes with many other people, building networks of combined knowledge that are continually growing with each generation. Science, architecture, technology, writing &ndash; in short, everything that allows you to read this article &ndash; would be impossible without it. &nbsp;</p><p>--&nbsp;</p><p><em>David Robson is BBC Future&rsquo;s feature writer. He is </em><a href=\\\"https://twitter.com/d_a_robson\\\">@d_a_robson</a><em> on Twitter</em>.<em></p><p></em><em>Join 700,000+ Future fans by liking us on </em><a href=\\\"https://www.facebook.com/BBCFuture\\\"><em>Facebook</em></a><em>, or follow us on </em><a href=\\\"https://twitter.com/bbc_future\\\"><em>Twitter</em></a><em>, </em><a href=\\\"https://plus.google.com/107828172298602173375/posts\\\"><em>Google+</em></a><em>, </em><a href=\\\"https://www.linkedin.com/company/bbc-com\\\"><em>LinkedIn</em></a><em> and </em><a href=\\\"https://instagram.com/bbcfuture_official/\\\"><em>Instagram</em></a><em>.</em></p><p><em>If you liked this story,&nbsp;</em><a href=\\\"http://pages.emails.bbc.com/subscribe/?ocid=fut.bbc.email.we.email-signup\\\"><em>sign up for the weekly bbc.com features newsletter</em></a><em>, called &ldquo;If You Only Read 6 Things This Week&rdquo;. A handpicked selection of stories from BBC Future, Earth, Culture, Capital, Travel and Autos, delivered to your inbox every Friday.</em></p>\",\"BusinessUnit\":\"worldwide\",\"CalloutBody\":\"<p>This story is part of a series inspired by the subjects and speakers appearing at <a href=\\\"https://www.worldchangingideas.com.au/world-changing-ideas-summit-2016\\\">BBC Future&rsquo;s World-Changing Ideas Summit</a> in Sydney on 15 November. Find out more about the <a href=\\\"https://www.worldchangingideas.com.au/world-changing-ideas-summit-2016/Speakers\\\">inspiring people coming to the meeting</a>, including:&nbsp;</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Psychologist <em><strong>Thomas Suddendorf</strong></em> on the traits that make us human</li>\\n<li>Researcher <strong><em>Helen Christensen</em></strong> on how tech can spot and treat mental health issues</li>\\n<li>BBC TV presenter&nbsp;<strong><em>Michael Mosley</em></strong>&nbsp;on the science of food and health</li>\\n<li>Uber&rsquo;s&nbsp;<strong><em>Kevin Corti</em></strong>&nbsp;on the hidden patterns of city transport</li>\\n<li>Researcher and TV presenter <strong><em>Emma Johnston</em></strong> on the impact of cities on oceans</li>\\n<li>Experimental architect <strong><em>Rachel Armstrong</em></strong> on interstellar travel</li>\\n<li>Astronauts&nbsp;<strong><em>Ron Garan</em></strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong><em>Andrew Thomas</em></strong>&nbsp;</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p class=\\\"p1\\\">+ many more</p>\",\"CalloutPosition\":\"top\",\"CalloutSubtitle\":\"The World-Changing Ideas Summit\",\"CalloutTitle\":\"Upcoming event\",\"Campaign\":null,\"Collection\":[],\"DisableAdverts\":false,\"DisplayDate\":\"2016-11-09T14:47:46Z\",\"Geolocation\":null,\"HeadlineLong\":\"We\u2019ve got human intelligence all wrong\",\"HeadlineShort\":\"We\u2019ve got human intelligence all wrong\",\"HideRelated\":false,\"Horizontal\":null,\"HyperHorizontal\":null,\"Intro\":\"When it comes to brainpower, we humans think our minds are the bees\u2019 knees \u2013 but are we really much smarter than other animals?\",\"IsSyndicated\":true,\"Latitude\":\"\",\"Location\":null,\"Longitude\":\"\",\"Option\":[],\"Partner\":null,\"PrimaryVertical\":\"wwfuture\",\"Programme\":null,\"RelatedStory\":[],\"RelatedTag\":null,\"StoryType\":\"image\",\"SummaryLong\":\"When it comes to brainpower, we humans think our minds are the bees\u2019 knees \u2013 but are we really as smart as we think?\",\"SummaryShort\":\"We are only different from animals in one crucial respect\",\"SuperSection\":null,\"Tag\":[]},\"Metadata\":{\"CreationDateTime\":\"2016-11-09T02:10:56.333359Z\",\"Entity\":\"story\",\"Guid\":\"9ee12cab-9c6b-4f54-a71c-a66de56075c3\",\"Id\":\"wwfuture/story/20161108-weve-got-human-intelligence-all-wrong\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"2016-12-16T15:05:05.077663Z\",\"Project\":\"wwfuture\",\"Slug\":\"20161108-weve-got-human-intelligence-all-wrong\"},\"Urn\":\"urn:pubstack:jative:story:wwfuture/story/20161108-weve-got-human-intelligence-all-wrong\",\"_id\":\"5b424596fa2f32dd66d796df\"}],\"RelatedTag\":null,\"StoryType\":\"video\",\"SummaryLong\":\"In little more than 50 years, we have gone from staring up at the heavens to the first tentative steps to colonising another planet.\\n\",\"SummaryShort\":\"Humanity\u2019s giant leaps into the unknown \",\"Tag\":[{\"Content\":{\"AssetImage\":null,\"Description\":\"\",\"LinkUrl\":\"\",\"Name\":\"Space\",\"CreationDateTime\":\"2014-09-02T14:02:02Z\",\"Entity\":\"tag\",\"Guid\":\"0dde5e36-9628-4922-a41e-823f38715f34\",\"Id\":\"tag/space\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"2015-09-03T09:04:07.217588Z\",\"Project\":\"\",\"Slug\":\"space\"},\"Metadata\":{\"CreationDateTime\":\"2014-09-02T14:02:02Z\",\"Entity\":\"tag\",\"Guid\":\"0dde5e36-9628-4922-a41e-823f38715f34\",\"Id\":\"tag/space\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"2015-09-03T09:04:07.217588Z\",\"Project\":\"\",\"Slug\":\"space\"},\"Urn\":\"urn:pubstack:jative:tag:tag/space\",\"_id\":\"5b3b1c02fa2f32dd66d3bd63\"}],\"CreationDateTime\":\"2016-11-11T14:20:14.693812Z\",\"Entity\":\"story\",\"Guid\":\"50612b94-5625-4c67-88dc-bc9acb699214\",\"Id\":\"wwfuture/story/20161111-how-humanity-took-a-bold-leap-into-the-cosmos\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"2016-11-11T14:40:55.217945Z\",\"Project\":\"wwfuture\",\"Slug\":\"20161111-how-humanity-took-a-bold-leap-into-the-cosmos\"},\"Metadata\":{\"CreationDateTime\":\"2016-11-11T14:20:14.693812Z\",\"Entity\":\"story\",\"Guid\":\"50612b94-5625-4c67-88dc-bc9acb699214\",\"Id\":\"wwfuture/story/20161111-how-humanity-took-a-bold-leap-into-the-cosmos\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"2016-11-11T14:40:55.217945Z\",\"Project\":\"wwfuture\",\"Slug\":\"20161111-how-humanity-took-a-bold-leap-into-the-cosmos\"},\"Urn\":\"urn:pubstack:jative:story:wwfuture/story/20161111-how-humanity-took-a-bold-leap-into-the-cosmos\",\"_id\":\"5b46f2e0fa2f32dd66da0e2e\"},{\"Content\":{\"AssetCustom\":\"\",\"AssetIbroadcast\":null,\"AssetImage\":[{\"Content\":{\"Copyright\":\"iStock\",\"FileSizeBytes\":306672,\"MimeType\":\"image/jpeg\",\"SourceHeight\":1080,\"SourceUrl\":\"https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/live-galileo-interface-mt-resources-imagebucket-1a92e5tj3b5d6/p0/4f/qx/p04fqxvn.jpg\",\"SourceWidth\":1920,\"SynopsisLong\":\"\",\"SynopsisMedium\":\"\",\"SynopsisShort\":\"(Credit: iStock)\",\"TemplateUrl\":\"http://ichef.bbci.co.uk/wwfeatures/$recipe/images/live/p0/4f/qx/p04fqxvn.jpg\",\"Title\":\"feet_istock_1920.jpg\",\"CreationDateTime\":\"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z\",\"Entity\":\"\",\"Guid\":\"\",\"Id\":\"p04fqxvn\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z\",\"Project\":\"\",\"Slug\":\"\"},\"Metadata\":{\"CreationDateTime\":\"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z\",\"Entity\":\"\",\"Guid\":\"\",\"Id\":\"p04fqxvn\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z\",\"Project\":\"\",\"Slug\":\"\"},\"Urn\":\"urn:pubstack:jative:image:p04fqxvn\",\"_id\":\"5b421de7fa2f32dd66d7817f\"}],\"AssetImagePromo\":null,\"AssetInfographic\":\"\",\"AssetInline\":[{\"Content\":{\"Copyright\":\"iStock\",\"FileSizeBytes\":85625,\"MimeType\":\"image/jpeg\",\"SourceHeight\":1080,\"SourceUrl\":\"https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/live-galileo-interface-mt-resources-imagebucket-1a92e5tj3b5d6/p0/4f/qx/p04fqxf6.jpg\",\"SourceWidth\":1920,\"SynopsisLong\":\"\",\"SynopsisMedium\":\"Maintaining muscle mass is just as important as cardiovascular exercise, experts say (Credit: iStock)\",\"SynopsisShort\":\"(Credit: iStock)\",\"TemplateUrl\":\"http://ichef.bbci.co.uk/wwfeatures/$recipe/images/live/p0/4f/qx/p04fqxf6.jpg\",\"Title\":\"weights_istock_1920.jpg\"},\"Metadata\":{\"CreationDateTime\":\"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z\",\"Entity\":\"\",\"Guid\":\"\",\"Id\":\"p04fqxf6\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z\",\"Project\":\"\",\"Slug\":\"\"},\"Urn\":\"urn:pubstack:jative:image:p04fqxf6\",\"_id\":\"5b467612fa2f32dd66d9cbe3\"},{\"Content\":{\"Copyright\":\"iStock\",\"FileSizeBytes\":134581,\"MimeType\":\"image/jpeg\",\"SourceHeight\":1080,\"SourceUrl\":\"https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/live-galileo-interface-mt-resources-imagebucket-1a92e5tj3b5d6/p0/4f/qy/p04fqyb3.jpg\",\"SourceWidth\":1920,\"SynopsisLong\":\"\",\"SynopsisMedium\":\"Chocolate milk may be as effective as more expensive exercise supplements, thanks to its ratio of carbs to protein (Credit: iStock)\",\"SynopsisShort\":\"(Credit: iStock)\",\"TemplateUrl\":\"http://ichef.bbci.co.uk/wwfeatures/$recipe/images/live/p0/4f/qy/p04fqyb3.jpg\",\"Title\":\"choc_istock_1920.jpg\"},\"Metadata\":{\"CreationDateTime\":\"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z\",\"Entity\":\"\",\"Guid\":\"\",\"Id\":\"p04fqyb3\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z\",\"Project\":\"\",\"Slug\":\"\"},\"Urn\":\"urn:pubstack:jative:image:p04fqyb3\",\"_id\":\"5b42e39bfa2f32dd66d7eab8\"}],\"AssetSelect\":\"\",\"AssetVideoIb2\":null,\"AssetVideoMps\":null,\"Author\":[{\"Content\":{\"AssetImage\":null,\"Description\":\"<p>David Robson is BBC Future's feature writer. Follow him on Twitter: <a href=\\\"https://twitter.com/d_a_robson\\\">@d_a_robson</a></p>\",\"Email\":[],\"Links\":null,\"Name\":\"David Robson\",\"PrimaryVertical\":\"wwfuture\"},\"Metadata\":{\"CreationDateTime\":\"2014-11-18T09:12:48Z\",\"Entity\":\"author\",\"Guid\":\"e78c4491-f8c5-4e20-9aeb-666a803ff880\",\"Id\":\"wwfuture/author/david-robson\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"2017-05-24T08:57:17.182645Z\",\"Project\":\"wwfuture\",\"Slug\":\"david-robson\"},\"Urn\":\"urn:pubstack:jative:author:wwfuture/author/david-robson\",\"_id\":\"5b3b1a4bfa2f32dd66d1b8bd\"}],\"BodyHtml\":\"<p><a href=\\\"http://www.bbc.com/future/columns/world-changing-ideas\\\"><img src=\\\"http://ichef.bbci.co.uk/images/ic/raw/p049vjvx.png\\\" border=\\\"0\\\" alt=\\\"World-changing ideas summit\\\" width=\\\"100%\\\" /></a></p><p>On paper, it seems like a no-brainer &ndash; exercise regularly and we can look better, feel stronger and live longer.</p><p>In reality, it&rsquo;s hard for many of us to muster the motivation to see it through. We may start the year with good intentions, only to find that our determination has mysteriously evaporated a few weeks later. And even if we do put in the hard work, we may not be able to see any tangible benefits, leaving us with the nagging doubt that we&rsquo;ve been wasting our time with a bad regime.</p><p>While there&rsquo;s no easy way to build a healthier body, science can offer some answers, revealing which strategies will bring out the best results with the least amount of effort. We&rsquo;ll be exploring the science of fitness at the <a href=\\\"https://www.worldchangingideas.com.au/world-changing-ideas-summit-2016\\\">BBC Future&rsquo;s World-Changing Ideas Summit in Sydney on 15 November</a>. In the meantime, here are some answers to your more pressing questions.</p><p><strong>DO I NEED TO STRETCH BEFORE I EXERCISE?</strong></p><p>A quick pre-workout stretch certainly won&rsquo;t do you any harm, but the evidence suggests it&rsquo;s probably not that useful either. Three large, randomised trials all show that <a href=\\\"http://www.nhs.uk/Livewell/fitness/Pages/Do-I-need-to-stretch-before-or-after-a-run-or-sports-and-exercise.aspx\\\">it won&rsquo;t reduce your risk of strain or injury</a>. Nor does it reduce the tender soreness you may feel the next morning. If you want to make the most of your time, you'd do better to start and end your session with some light aerobic exercise, which will warm up the muscles and burn some calories at the same time.</p><p><strong>ARE WEIGHTS JUST FOR ATHLETES AND BODY-BUILDERS?</strong></p><p>No. Although regular cardiovascular exercise is important, weight training can bring you many benefits that are not just aesthetic. Muscle can regulate your levels of insulin and blood sugar, <a href=\\\"http://cpr.sagepub.com/content/20/6/1051.short\\\">helping you to fight type 2 diabetes</a>, <a href=\\\"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3496010/\\\">improving your overall cardiovascular health and reducing your risk of cancer</a>.</p><p>{\\\"image\\\":{\\\"pid\\\":\\\"p04fqxf6\\\"}}</p><p>Bulking up may be particularly important for the elderly, who are at a high risk of losing muscle and bone mass, with studies showing that regular resistance training may <a href=\\\"http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s40279-016-0507-z\\\">improve mobility and help to prevent issues like lower back pain</a> and <a href=\\\"http://www.webmd.com/osteoporosis/features/exercise-for-osteoporosis\\\">osteoporosis</a>.</p><p><strong>WHAT SUPPLEMENTS SHOULD I USE?</strong></p><p>Health food shops are full of post-workout shakes to help your muscles recover from exertion, but a cheaper alternative may be <a href=\\\"http://www.karger.com/article/abstract/341954\\\">plain old chocolate milk</a>. It contains the perfect four-to-one ratio of carbs to protein, which <a href=\\\"https://jissn.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/1550-2783-9-S1-P3\\\">helps rebuild the workout tissue</a>, and also helps replace the electrolytes, like sodium, that are necessary for muscle contraction and which are depleted during exercise, causing cramps. And it&rsquo;s tasty.</p><p><strong>WHAT&rsquo;S THE DEAL WITH &lsquo;HIGH-INTENSITY TRAINING&rsquo;?</strong></p><p>If spending most your free time in the gym doesn&rsquo;t appeal, High-Intensity Training (Hit) involves short bursts of intense exercise, amounting to only a few minutes a session. The approach does not work for everyone &ndash; there&rsquo;s evidence that around <a href=\\\"http://www.bbc.com/news/health-17177251\\\">20% of people find no benefit</a>, while 15% will make huge strides, bringing many of the same benefits as hours of conventional workouts, including improved aerobic fitness and improved insulin sensitivity. This may be due to genetic differences in the ways our cells respond to strain.</p><p>{\\\"image\\\":{\\\"pid\\\":\\\"p04fqyb3\\\"}}</p><p>WCIS speaker Michael Mosley put the idea to the test in an <a href=\\\"http://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-37249021\\\">article for BBC News</a>, attempting just a few minutes of Hit a week for four weeks. The regime involved warming up on an exercise bike for a couple of minutes, and then going full throttle for 20 seconds. He then repeated the cycle once more before finishing his exercise for the week.</p><p>In <a href=\\\"http://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-37249021\\\">another (slightly more arduous) experiment</a>, participants trying 15 minutes of Hit a week found a 16% drop in their blood pressure and a 17% increase in the amount of oxygen in their blood &ndash; a measure of how well their heart and lungs are functioning.</p><p>Clearly, Hit isn&rsquo;t for everyone, and you would should consult a doctor if you are unused to strenuous exercise, or on medication, but it may be a good alternative for people struggling to slot gym trips into their already packed schedule.</p><p>--</p><p><em>Join 700,000+ Future fans by liking us on </em><a href=\\\"https://www.facebook.com/BBCFuture\\\"><em>Facebook</em></a><em>, or follow us on </em><a href=\\\"https://twitter.com/bbc_future\\\"><em>Twitter</em></a><em>, </em><a href=\\\"https://plus.google.com/107828172298602173375/posts\\\"><em>Google+</em></a><em>, </em><a href=\\\"https://www.linkedin.com/company/bbc-com\\\"><em>LinkedIn</em></a><em> and </em><a href=\\\"https://instagram.com/bbcfuture_official/\\\"><em>Instagram</em></a><em>.</em></p><p><em>If you liked this story,&nbsp;</em><a href=\\\"http://pages.emails.bbc.com/subscribe/?ocid=fut.bbc.email.we.email-signup\\\"><em>sign up for the weekly bbc.com features newsletter</em></a><em>, called &ldquo;If You Only Read 6 Things This Week&rdquo;. A handpicked selection of stories from BBC Future, Earth, Culture, Capital, Travel and Autos, delivered to your inbox every Friday.</em><em><br /></em></p>\",\"BusinessUnit\":\"worldwide\",\"CalloutBody\":\"<ul>\\n<li>BBC TV presenter Michael Mosley on the science of food and health</li>\\n<li>Researcher Helen Christensen on how tech can spot and treat mental health issues</li>\\n<li>Uber&rsquo;s Kevin Corti on the hidden patterns of city transport</li>\\n<li>Researcher and TV presenter Emma Johnston on the impact of cities on oceans</li>\\n<li>Experimental architect Rachel Armstrong on interstellar travel</li>\\n<li>Astronauts Ron Garan and Andrew Thomas</li>\\n<li>+ many more</li>\\n</ul>\",\"CalloutPosition\":\"top\",\"CalloutSubtitle\":\"The World-Changing Ideas Summit\",\"CalloutTitle\":\"Upcoming event\",\"Campaign\":null,\"Collection\":[{\"Content\":{\"AssetImage\":[],\"Campaign\":null,\"CollectionOverrides\":null,\"CollectionType\":\"column\",\"Description\":\"Fascinating stories, need-to-know briefings and compelling video inspired by BBC Future's World-Changing Ideas event series, next on in Sydney on 15 November 2016.\",\"Name\":\"World-Changing Ideas\",\"Partner\":null,\"PrimaryVertical\":\"wwfuture\",\"Title\":\"World-Changing Ideas\",\"CreationDateTime\":\"2015-05-20T11:04:06.894444Z\",\"Entity\":\"collection\",\"Guid\":\"58a318ae-63bd-40fd-953b-a783283ba763\",\"Id\":\"wwfuture/column/world-changing-ideas\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"2016-10-12T12:27:58.674723Z\",\"Project\":\"wwfuture\",\"Slug\":\"column/world-changing-ideas\"},\"Metadata\":{\"CreationDateTime\":\"2015-05-20T11:04:06.894444Z\",\"Entity\":\"collection\",\"Guid\":\"58a318ae-63bd-40fd-953b-a783283ba763\",\"Id\":\"wwfuture/column/world-changing-ideas\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"2016-10-12T12:27:58.674723Z\",\"Project\":\"wwfuture\",\"Slug\":\"column/world-changing-ideas\"},\"Urn\":\"urn:pubstack:jative:collection:wwfuture/column/world-changing-ideas\",\"_id\":\"5b3b1a4ffa2f32dd66d1be96\"}],\"DisableAdverts\":false,\"DisplayDate\":\"2016-11-11T13:47:24Z\",\"Geolocation\":null,\"HeadlineLong\":\"How to get fit with minimum time and effort\",\"HeadlineShort\":\"How to get in shape by Christmas\",\"HideRelated\":false,\"Horizontal\":null,\"HyperHorizontal\":null,\"Intro\":\"We all need to exercise. But how can we get what we need without spending all the time in the gym?\",\"IsSyndicated\":false,\"Latitude\":\"\",\"Location\":null,\"Longitude\":\"\",\"Option\":[{\"Content\":{\"Description\":\"Apple News Publish: Select to publish, remove to unpublish. (Do not just delete or unpublish the story)\",\"Name\":\"publish-applenews-system-1\"},\"Metadata\":{\"CreationDateTime\":\"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z\",\"Entity\":\"option\",\"Guid\":\"13f4bc85-ae27-4a34-9397-0e6ad3619619\",\"Id\":\"option/publish-applenews-system-1\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z\",\"Project\":\"\",\"Slug\":\"publish-applenews-system-1\"},\"Urn\":\"urn:pubstack:jative:option:option/publish-applenews-system-1\",\"_id\":\"5b3b1b3cfa2f32dd66d32e6f\"}],\"Partner\":null,\"PrimaryVertical\":\"wwfuture\",\"Programme\":null,\"RelatedStory\":[{\"Content\":{\"AssetCustom\":\"\",\"AssetIbroadcast\":null,\"AssetImage\":[],\"AssetImagePromo\":null,\"AssetInfographic\":\"\",\"AssetInline\":[],\"AssetSelect\":\"\",\"AssetVideoIb2\":null,\"AssetVideoMps\":null,\"Author\":[],\"BodyHtml\":\"<p>Sweet, sour, bitter, salty and &ndash; ah yes, umami. It&rsquo;s the somewhat ineffable savoury flavour that makes certain foods so moreish. It was first proposed as one of the basic tastes by a Japanese chemist named Kikunae Ikeda.</p><p>Ikeda realised that the seaweed broth he loved was so tasty in part because it had a pseudo-meaty quality. After some analysis of his dinner one day, he realised that it contained glutamate crystals responsible for this flavour. A stable form of the same chemical, monosodium glutamate &ndash; better known as MSG &ndash; was soon patented, branded as Ajinomoto, and used in food products all over the world.</p><p>In the year 2000, scientists discovered that humans have a specific <a href=\\\"http://www.nature.com/neuro/journal/v3/n2/full/nn0200_99.html\\\">taste receptor for that umami flavour</a> which helps to explain the popularity of MSG. Cheese, bacon, and chips with ketchup also contain natural forms of glutamate that trigger the umami receptor &ndash; explaining why we often crave these super savoury foods.</p><p>Watch the video below to understand why we are born to love these foods, the truth about the risks of eating too much artificial MSG.</p><p>{\\\"image\\\":{\\\"pid\\\":\\\"p04f5qb5\\\"}}</p><p>--</p><p><em>Follow </em><a href=\\\"https://www.youtube.com/user/HeadsqueezeTV\\\"><em>BritLab's YouTube channel </em></a><em>and join 700,000+ Future fans by liking us on</em> <a href=\\\"https://www.facebook.com/BBCFuture\\\"><strong><em>Facebook</em></strong></a><em>, or follow us on</em> <a href=\\\"https://twitter.com/bbc_future\\\"><strong><em>Twitter</em></strong></a><em>,</em> <a href=\\\"https://plus.google.com/107828172298602173375/posts\\\"><strong><em>Google+</em></strong></a><em>,</em> <a href=\\\"https://www.linkedin.com/company/bbc-com\\\"><strong><em>LinkedIn</em></strong></a> <em>and </em><a href=\\\"https://instagram.com/bbcfuture_official/\\\"><strong><em>Instagram.</em></strong></a></p><p><em>If you liked this story,&nbsp;</em><a href=\\\"http://pages.emails.bbc.com/subscribe/?ocid=fut.bbc.email.we.email-signup\\\"><em>sign up for the weekly bbc.com features newsletter</em></a><em>, called &ldquo;If You Only Read 6 Things This Week&rdquo;. A handpicked selection of stories from BBC Future, Earth, Culture, Capital, Travel and Autos, delivered to your inbox every Friday.</em>&nbsp;</p>\",\"BusinessUnit\":\"worldwide\",\"CalloutBody\":\"\",\"CalloutPosition\":\"\",\"CalloutSubtitle\":\"\",\"CalloutTitle\":\"\",\"Campaign\":null,\"Collection\":[],\"DisableAdverts\":false,\"DisplayDate\":\"2016-09-30T09:36:13.191Z\",\"Geolocation\":null,\"HeadlineLong\":\"Why we crave cheese, bacon and ketchup\",\"HeadlineShort\":\"Why we crave cheese, bacon and ketchup\",\"HideRelated\":false,\"Horizontal\":null,\"HyperHorizontal\":null,\"Intro\":\"There\u2019s a good reason why we find some foods so addictive - as the video below explains.\",\"IsSyndicated\":false,\"Latitude\":\"\",\"Location\":null,\"Longitude\":\"\",\"Option\":null,\"Partner\":null,\"PrimaryVertical\":\"wwfuture\",\"Programme\":null,\"RelatedStory\":[],\"RelatedTag\":null,\"StoryType\":\"video\",\"SummaryLong\":\"There\u2019s a good reason why we find some foods so addictive.\",\"SummaryShort\":\"There\u2019s a good reason why we find some foods so addictive \",\"SuperSection\":null,\"Tag\":null},\"Metadata\":{\"CreationDateTime\":\"2016-09-30T08:44:36.907485Z\",\"Entity\":\"story\",\"Guid\":\"85702297-0bb2-4770-8ade-722b56bd9089\",\"Id\":\"wwfuture/story/20160930-why-we-crave-cheese-bacon-and-ketchup\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"2016-11-11T21:45:34.557132Z\",\"Project\":\"wwfuture\",\"Slug\":\"20160930-why-we-crave-cheese-bacon-and-ketchup\"},\"Urn\":\"urn:pubstack:jative:story:wwfuture/story/20160930-why-we-crave-cheese-bacon-and-ketchup\",\"_id\":\"5b46fca5fa2f32dd66da1355\"},{\"Content\":{\"AssetCustom\":\"\",\"AssetIbroadcast\":null,\"AssetImage\":[],\"AssetImagePromo\":null,\"AssetInfographic\":\"time-of-day/\",\"AssetInline\":null,\"AssetSelect\":\"infographic\",\"AssetVideoIb2\":null,\"AssetVideoMps\":null,\"Author\":null,\"BodyHtml\":\"<p><em>Created by <a href=\\\"http://beyondwordsstudio.com/\\\">Beyond Words Studio</a> for BBC Future</em></p>\",\"BusinessUnit\":\"worldwide\",\"CalloutBody\":\"\",\"CalloutPosition\":\"\",\"CalloutSubtitle\":\"\",\"CalloutTitle\":\"\",\"Campaign\":null,\"Collection\":[],\"DisableAdverts\":false,\"DisplayDate\":\"2016-07-04T11:09:02Z\",\"Geolocation\":null,\"HeadlineLong\":\"Interactive: Your 24-hour guide to living a smarter day \",\"HeadlineShort\":\"When should you have your first coffee?\",\"HideRelated\":false,\"Horizontal\":null,\"Intro\":\"When should you drink your first cup of coffee \u2013 or your first beer? At what time is it best to send an important email? And what\u2019s a simple trick to improve your chances of a good night\u2019s sleep? Enter your details and discover the perfect schedule.\",\"IsSyndicated\":true,\"Location\":null,\"Option\":null,\"Partner\":null,\"PrimaryVertical\":\"wwfuture\",\"Programme\":null,\"RelatedStory\":null,\"RelatedTag\":[],\"StoryType\":\"infographic\",\"SummaryLong\":\"A personalised infographic to uncover the hidden rhythms governing your life.\",\"SummaryShort\":\"Take a personalised, interactive guide to living a smarter day\",\"SuperSection\":null,\"Tag\":[]},\"Metadata\":{\"CreationDateTime\":\"2016-07-04T02:16:42.83955Z\",\"Entity\":\"story\",\"Guid\":\"50dc04d2-8704-4697-a6d8-5a3128e06ca6\",\"Id\":\"wwfuture/story/20160630-infographic-a-24-hour-guide-to-your-brain-and-body\",\"ModifiedDateTime\":\"2017-02-20T10:40:19.72738Z\",\"Project\":\"wwfuture\",\"Slug\":\"20160630-infographic-a-24-hour-guide-to-your-brain-and-body\"},\"Urn\":\"urn:pubstack:jative:story:wwfuture/story/20160630-infographic-a-24-hour-guide-to-your-brain-and-body\",\"_id\":\"5b425788fa2f32dd66d7a023\"},{\"Content\":{\"AssetCustom\":\"\",\"AssetIbroadcast\":null,\"AssetImage\":[],\"AssetImagePromo\":null,\"AssetInfographic\":\"\",\"AssetInline\":[],\"AssetSelect\":\"\",\"AssetVideoIb2\":null,\"AssetVideoMps\":null,\"Author\":[],\"BodyHtml\":\"<p>Before you head to the gym, here are seven fascinating insights from science to help motivate you and get more from your exercise, plucked from the BBC Future archive:</p><p><strong>1. Why exercise boosts IQ</strong></p><p>Consider this: children who walk to school concentrate better and get better test results; older people who enjoy mild exercise are half as likely to suffer from cognitive impairments</p><p>It&rsquo;s thought that the extra blood supply to the brain promotes the growth of neurons and encourages the release of certain neurotransmitters and growth hormones that are crucial to the brain&rsquo;s overall health.</p><p><em><a href=\\\"http://www.bbc.com/future/story/20141010-why-exercise-boosts-iq\\\">Watch this video by Britlab to learn more</a>. </em></p><p>{\\\"image\\\":{\\\"pid\\\":\\\"p028dmlv\\\"}}</p><p><strong>2. The psychology of workout music</strong></p><p>Which songs get you pumped up for working out? Many of us think exercising to music helps to reduce effort and increase endurance. Why does music have this effect? The answer <a href=\\\"http://www.bbc.com/future/story/20130618-the-psychology-of-workout-music\\\">lies in our brains, not in our muscles, says Tom Stafford in his article on the subject</a>.</p><p>The effect seems to be most pronounced for self-paced exercises &ndash; running or rowing rather than team sports. The area of the brain that signals the movement of muscles is called the motor cortex. This is where we plan to make movements and it&rsquo;s especially critical for the timing of actions.</p><p>The signal from our music travels down our auditory pathways to the supplementary motor area where, says Stafford, the rhythm of the music may help with the process of timing our actions.</p><p><strong>3. Are cramps caused by a lack of salt?</strong></p><p>The cause of cramps is something of a mystery. Because they are so difficult to predict, trying to cause one in a lab is not easy, so most studies look at real-life observations.</p><p>Studies on American footballers show that cramps are more likely to happen in hot weather, which fits with the theory that they are caused by low salt levels, lost through sweat. The problem with this is that athletes in cold climates get cramp too.</p><p>Another study on South African ultra-marathon runners found little difference in sodium levels between athletes that cramped up and those that didn&rsquo;t. The advice if you are suffering from cramp is to stretch it out. There&rsquo;s no need to increase levels of sodium.</p><p><em><a href=\\\"http://www.bbc.com/future/story/20120430-are-cramps-due-to-lack-of-salt\\\">Read more about the cause of cramps here</a>. </em></p><p>{\\\"image\\\":{\\\"pid\\\":\\\"p01bl0g7\\\"}}</p><p><strong>4. Is stretching before and after exercise necessary?</strong></p><p>We&rsquo;re often told that stretching our muscles is the best way to avoid aching limbs the following day or injuries during sport. But is this true?</p><p>Two studies have both pointed towards an answer: not really. <a href=\\\"http://www.bbc.com/future/story/20120724-you-must-stretch-before-exercise\\\">In this article by Claudia Hammond</a>, Rob Herbert from the George Institute in Australia &ndash; the author of one of the two reviews &ndash; told us that if you enjoy stretching before exercise, you&rsquo;re fine to carry on, but it probably won't help much. All the evidence points towards little difference in muscle recovery or injury prevention.</p><p><strong>5. Do special running shoes prevent injury?</strong></p><p>If you&rsquo;re a keen runner you might have been fitted for personalised running shoes. For this you probably had to run in front of a shop assistant while they told you how much you &ldquo;pronate&rdquo; (turn your foot inwards on impact with the floor). But does it matter?</p><p>The evidence for the benefits of specialised footwear is so sparse that some consider it a myth. Surprisingly, even the evidence that running on hard surfaces leads to more injuries is weak. But footwear manufacturers will still try to make shoes with claims of better support and injury prevention.</p><p><em><a href=\\\"http://www.bbc.com/future/story/20131002-do-running-shoes-prevent-injury\\\">Read more about the evidence here</a>. </em></p><p>{\\\"image\\\":{\\\"pid\\\":\\\"p00xq9s3\\\"}}</p><p><strong>6. &nbsp;Will we ever run 100m in under nine seconds?</strong></p><p>If you're a more determined athlete, you might want to set yourself an ambitious target. But what are the limits of human capability? <a href=\\\"http://www.bbc.com/future/story/20120712-will-we-ever-run-100m-in-9-secs\\\">Ed Yong explored this for us</a>, and unsurprisingly found it a difficult question to answer.</p><p>For most runners, speed is largely determined by how much force they can apply when their foot is on the ground, so there are two options for increasing speed; hit the ground harder or exert the same force for a longer period. Studies show that the calf muscles more than any other determine the amount of force that runners apply to the ground.</p><p>People are getting faster but in unpredictable ways. Current estimates show that we&rsquo;ve yet to reach the ceiling of human speed.</p><p><strong>7. Does exercise really help with depression?</strong></p><p>The best evidence for the effect of exercise on mood comes from one of the largest meta-analyses of data analysed by Cochrane. They looked at data from 30 trials in countries as diverse as Thailand, Denmark and Australia and came to the conclusion that on the whole exercise might have benefits for people suffering from depression, but the effect is very, very small. It&rsquo;s certainly not the panacea some claim it to be.</p><p><em><a href=\\\"http://www.bbc.com/future/story/20120822-does-exercise-help-depression\\\">Read more about the effects of exercise on mood here</a></em><em>.</em></p><p>-</p><p><em>Join 500,000+ Future fans by liking us on</em> <a href=\\\"https://www.facebook.com/BBCFuture\\\"><em>Facebook</em></a><em>, or follow us on </em><a href=\\\"https://twitter.com/bbc_future\\\"><em>Twitter</em></a><em>, </em><a href=\\\"https://plus.google.com/107828172298602173375/posts\\\"><em>Google+</em></a><em>, </em><a href=\\\"https://www.linkedin.com/company/bbc-com\\\"><em>LinkedIn</em></a><em> and </em><a href=\\\"https://instagram.com/bbcfuture_official/\\\"><em>Instagram</em></a><em>.</em></p><p><em>If you liked this story,&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http://pages.emails.bbc.com/subscribe/\\\">sign up for the weekly bbc.com features newsletter</a></em><em>, called &ldquo;</em><em>If You Only Read 6 Things This Week</em><em>&rdquo;. A handpicked selection of stories from BBC Future, Earth, Culture, Capital, Travel and Autos, delivered to your inbox every Friday.</em></p>\",\"BusinessUnit\":\"worldwide\",\"CalloutBody\":\"\",\"CalloutPosition\":\"\",\"CalloutSubtitle\":\"\",\"CalloutTitle\":\"\",\"Campaign\":null,\"Collection\":null,\"DisableAdverts\":false,\"DisplayDate\":\"2016-01-22T12:34:13.652Z\",\"Geolocation\":null,\"HeadlineLong\":\"How to exercise smarter\",\"Headl